The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus led by Moses from Egypt.
I grew up with this myth.
The myth is swiftly told.
Die junge Kommunistische Partei und ihre drei Roten Armeen wurden Anfang der 1930er Jahre von Chiang Kai-sheks nationalistischer Regierung aus ihren Stützpunkten im Süden vertrieben.
Von ihren Feinden verfolgt und gepeinigt, überquerten sie hohe Gebirge, reißende Flüsse und unwegsames Weideland, wobei Mao den Zug von Sieg zu Sieg lenkte.
Nach zwei Jahren und 16.000 Kilometern der Standhaftigkeit, des Mutes und der Hoffnung entgegen unglaublich schlechten Aussichten erreichten die Roten Armeen Nordwestchina.
Nur ein Fünftel der 200.000 Soldaten war übrig geblieben – erschöpft, übel zugerichtet, aber voller Trotz.
Ein Jahrzehnt später schlugen sie zurück, besiegten Chiang Kai-shek und gründeten Maos Neues China.
To what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to trace its path.
It is still a frightening journey through regions that have changed little since then, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are left today. I found 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or made it to the end, but their stories were incredibly insightful.
Huan Zhiji was barely taller than his rifle when he joined the Red Army as a child.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought about fleeing the country, but stayed out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many fled.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Xiang River Battle, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
But at most 15,000 died in the battle; the rest disappeared.
Another battle, at the Dadu River, is at the center of the Long March legend. Supposedly, 22 brave men overpowered a regiment of Nationalist troops guarding the Luding Bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event of the entire Long March, and it is celebrated as such today.
But documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu initially told party historians a completely different story. "The matter wasn't as complicated as people later portrayed it," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth.
How it is portrayed is another matter."
So lives the legend on.
Over the Dadu, there was merely a skirmish.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The marchers did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
<s>Women were ordered to turn around and return home because there was not enough food.
<s>Just a month after the merger of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March must continue.
<s>However, it was saved by the capture of Chiang Kai-shek by the general Chiang had assigned to destroy the Communists.
<s>As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
<s>The Long March was over.
Nor for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, which was led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's top rival, and was tasked with crossing the western Chinese border to seek aid from Russia.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they neither fought nor retreated.
Consigned to barren land where survival was difficult, they were exterminated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is missing from the official history.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the party and deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages to extort ransom money.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers were left to command in battles.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They embraced their suffering with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.

<s>What drove them to do it?
<s>I asked one of the top generals what he knew about communism back then. "I didn't know then, and I don't know now," he answered. "In fact, I doubt even Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope of a just and progressive society.
<s>No one may have known – or could have known – how much suffering still lay ahead, how great the sacrifice would be, and how vast the gap between dream and reality would be.
